    "questions": [
        {
            "id": "defc0a406b464cacab61f",
            "questionText": "A proton with a charge of $!$1.602 \\times 10^{-19} \\text{ C}$!$, a mass of $!$1.672 \\times 10^{-27} \\text{ kg}$!$, and an initial velocity of $!$5 \\times 10^6 \\text{ m/s}$!$ (which is perpendicular to a uniform magnetic field of strength $!$0.5 \\text{ T}$!$) is injected into the magnetic field. Given these conditions, how long will it take for the proton to complete one revolution around its circular path?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "0a5c1361280041fc8633f",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate formula that relates the mass, velocity, charge, and magnetic field to the radius of the circular motion. Which of the following formulas correctly gives the radius?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f34446c8-9452-48c0-ab50-0cb3fd1b9679",
                        "9608ce91-85fd-4769-948b-5b32a202a3d0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$R = \\frac{mv}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$R = \\frac{qB}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$R = \\frac{mv^2}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a2c61d47fc9e425ca6463",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the correct formula for the radius, substitute the given values for mass ($!$m = 1.672 \\times 10^{-27}\\text{ kg}$!$), velocity ($!$v = 5 \\times 10^6\\text{ m/s}$!$), charge ($!$q = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19}\\text{ C}$!$), and magnetic field ($!$B = 0.5\\text{ T}$!$) into this formula. Calculate the radius of the circular path.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.104"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f34446c8-9452-48c0-ab50-0cb3fd1b9679",
                        "9608ce91-85fd-4769-948b-5b32a202a3d0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ddbefa81bcaa47a49c5f1",
                    "stepText": "Great job calculating the radius! Next, we need to find the time period for one complete revolution. Identify the correct formula that represents the time period (T) of the circular motion of a charged particle in a magnetic field.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0686c4f9-2dd6-4c52-b79a-a66dd4561b52"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{2\\pi m}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{m}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{2\\pi v}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "8fa60839773d4cbaaa23a",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the correct period formula, substitute the given values for mass, charge, and magnetic field to compute the time period for one complete revolution. What is the approximate time?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.31e-7"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0686c4f9-2dd6-4c52-b79a-a66dd4561b52"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "d07a4bdf4633490db3586",
            "questionText": "An electron, with charge $!$q = -1.602 \\times 10^{-19} C$!$ and mass $!$m = 9.11 \\times 10^{-31} kg$!$, is shot horizontally at an initial velocity of $!$u = 3 \\times 10^6 m/s$!$ into a uniform electric field between two parallel plates. The electric field strength is $!$E = 2000 N/C$!$, and the plates are $!$l = 0.1 m$!$ long. Determine the vertical displacement of the electron as it exits the region between the plates.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "0f17e87cde9c4d2b89391",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that relates the electric force to the resulting acceleration of a charged particle in an electric field. Which formula correctly represents the vertical acceleration of the electron when placed in an electric field?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "5c33bb63-3c6d-413f-a1af-25385ab95845"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = \\frac{qE}{m}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = \\frac{mE}{q}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = qEm$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "cce0020c51004aec87cf5",
                    "stepText": "Great, now compute the magnitude of the vertical acceleration using the formula you selected. Use the values \\(q = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19} C\\) (magnitude), \\(E = 2000 \\, N/C\\), and \\(m = 9.11 \\times 10^{-31} kg\\). What is the acceleration?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.52e14"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "5c33bb63-3c6d-413f-a1af-25385ab95845"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "02ad5063e6b74c6293013",
                    "stepText": "Now, as the electron travels horizontally between the plates, its speed remains constant. Determine the time it takes for the electron to traverse the length of the plates using the horizontal distance \\(l = 0.1 m\\) and the horizontal velocity \\(u = 3 \\times 10^6 m/s\\). What is the time spent in the electric field?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.33e-8"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "272ac608e6d84d0e93c99",
                    "stepText": "Next, identify the formula that gives the vertical displacement of a particle starting from rest under constant acceleration. Which formula correctly represents the vertical displacement in this scenario?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a5fee9d5-2b2a-4e9d-8caf-a83a70245740"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y = \\frac{1}{2}at^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y = at$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$y = \\frac{at^2}{u}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "52650d8552994b698e1ae",
                    "stepText": "Finally, calculate the vertical displacement by substituting the computed acceleration and time into the vertical displacement formula. What is the vertical displacement of the electron as it exits the plates?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
